<p>Hydrochloric acid is the first system studied by Zhang et al. for hydrometallurgical treatment of spent LIB recycling [
 <xref rid="B42-materials-13-00801" ref-type="bibr">42</xref>]. Frequently compared to H
 <sub>2</sub>SO
 <sub>4</sub> [
 <xref rid="B120-materials-13-00801" ref-type="bibr">120</xref>,
 <xref rid="B129-materials-13-00801" ref-type="bibr">129</xref>], HCl leaching also dissolves spent cathodic material in an efficient manner (&gt;95%). Chloride-based processes are summarized in 
 <xref ref-type="app" rid="app1-materials-13-00801">Tables S3 and S4</xref> in 
 <xref ref-type="app" rid="app1-materials-13-00801">Supplementary Materials</xref>. The dissolution reaction proposed by Meshram et al. involves reduction of transition metals (designated as M(III) or M(II) in the reactions) as the cathodic reaction and evolution of O
 <sub>2(g)</sub> as the anodic reaction [
 <xref rid="B114-materials-13-00801" ref-type="bibr">114</xref>]. 
